The execution context serialization format has changed from JSON to Base64 in Spring Batch 5, see [Execution context serialization updates](https://docs.spring.io/spring-batch/docs/current/reference/html/whatsnew.html#execution-context-serialization-updates).

You can use any Base64 decoder (or database function) to decode the content of the execution context. You can also configure Spring Batch to serialize the execution context to JSON as in the previous version. This can be done as follows:

```
@Configuration
@EnableBatchProcessing(executionContextSerializerRef = &quot;jacksonSerializer&quot;)
public class MyJobConfiguration {

    // Add job definition

    @Bean
    public ExecutionContextSerializer jacksonSerializer() {
        return new Jackson2ExecutionContextStringSerializer();
    }
}
```

You need to add the Jackson dependency to your project as well.

