The `@BeforeStep` annotated method is executed before the step (in which the reader is involved) is executed. In your test, there is no step running, so you should not be expecting this method to be called.

Moreover, you are injecting a job parameter in the `date` field, but the test does not prepare any job parameter, it rather adds the key/value par `[&quot;input.data&quot;=&quot;foo,bar,spam&quot;]` in the step execution context, which is not used by the reader.

So to answer your question about how to test a step-scoped bean that is configured with a job parameter, you need to:

1. Create a step execution prepared with your job parameter
2. Declare the reader as a Spring bean so that it gets proxied as needed
3. Autowire the reader in your test class and use `StepScopeTestUtils.doInStepScope` to simulate an execution within the scope of a step

